text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!PhonologicalPhenomenaInSpokenLanguages]]%0a%0a!Schwa deletion in Indian Languages %0a%0a:Author: Mihir_D%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aDifferent Indian languages have a phenomena of deleting schwas that would have been present%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aMany Indian languages belong to the Indo-Aryan branch of the Indo-European language family, with the modern languages descending partly from Sanskrit. Some of these languages feature the phenomenon of schwa deletion, where an implicit schwa (pronounced as /ə/ or /ɐ/) present in the Sanskrit root word and written script is not pronounced. An example language that heavily features this phenomenon is Hindi. A language that features only some aspects of schwa deletion is Marathi. %0a%0aThe a religious text "Veda" is spelled as वेद in Hindi, Marathi, and Sanskrit, but is pronounced differently:%0aSanskrit: [ʋedɐ]%0aMarathi: [ʋed]  (deleted schwa)%0aHindi: [ʋed]    (deleted schwa)%0a%0aWord final schwas seem to be deleted more often than medial ones in languages such as Marathi. Hindi tends delete schwas about 89%25 of the time when in an environment like VC_CV. %0a%0aThe word रचना has the same spelling and meaning in all 3 languages, but has different pronunciations: %0aSanskrit: [rətʃənaː]%0aMarathi: [rətʃənaː]%0aHindi: [rətʃnaː] (2nd schwa deleted)%0a%0aIn the US, many people debated how to pronounce Vice President Kamala Harris' first name, and part of the problem comes with Schwa deletion. In Hindi it would be pronounced [kəmlɐ]. But in Sanskrit or Tamil (her mother's native language) it is [kəməlɐ]. Her official pronunciation is based on this second form [kɑːmələ].%0a%0aInterestingly, the phenomenon seems to be changing Marathi. Due to high contact with languages such as Hindi, there has been an increase of schwa deletion in Marathi as well. I have seen this change in my own family, who all speak the language.%0a%0aThe words गुण and गोड were pronounced as [guɳə] and [goɖə] by people in my great-grandparents' generation and are pronounced as [guɳ] and [goɖ] now. The road my grandparents live on has the word मार्ग in its name. This is pronounced as [maɾɡə] by my grandparents, but more like [maɾɡ] (as it is in Hindi) by their younger neighbors. %0a%0aOne possible reason for this phenomenon is talking quickly. English (another Indo-European language) seems to feature some schwa deletion today as well. In these examples, the schwa before a stressless syllable is deleted if the word is said too quickly or in a sentence. %0a%0aOpera: [ɑpəɹə] -> [ɑpɹə]%0aGeneral:[d͡ʒɛnəɹəl] -> [d͡ʒɛnɹəl%0aChocolate: [t͡ʃɔkəlɪt] -> [t͡ʃɔklɪt]%0a%0aIn English schwa deletion does not occur word initially or finally, but may occur in the middle of a word.%0a%0aSources: %0ahttp://www.aellk.or.kr/datax/thesis/1613433509823.pdf%0ahttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Schwa_deletion_in_Indo-Aryan_languages%0a%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a#foxbegin 210330-222205-194770#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!An algorithmic approach to predicting schwa deletion %0a-> - aryans%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aResearchers in the Computer Science Department of IIT Kharagpur created an algorithm that, when given the written form of a Hindi word, predicts where the schwas will be deleted with 96.12 percent accuracy (tested on over 11000 words). The accuracy jumps to 99.89 percent when a morphological analyzer preprocesses the word and gives the algorithm information about the morphemes. The researchers create functions intended to be optimized (for example, the ease of articulation of a particular syllable) under certain constraints (for example, how much speakers can delete schwas before the meaning of the word becomes unclear). The algorithm tries to optimize these quantities, and has a runtime that is linear in the length of the word. The researchers also tested the algorithm on Bengali, in which case the accuracy was about 85 percent on 1000 randomly selected words. The researchers stress that their algorithm doesn't just outperform previous attempts; it also lays out a "constrained optimization based framework" to model phonological processes. %0a%0aSource: Choudhury, Monojit, Anupam Basu, and Sudeshna Sarkar. "A Diachronic Approach for Schwa Deletion in Indo-Aryan Languages" (2004)%0a   %0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210330-222205-194770#%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a(:section: A:)%0a(:Category: PhonologicalPhenomenaInSpokenLanguages:)
