diff:1617142925:1616909529:=76,87c76%0a%3c #foxbegin 210330-222205-194770#%0a%3c (:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a%3c !!!An algorithmic approach to predicting schwa deletion %0a%3c -> - aryans%0a%3c (:div1end:) %0a%3c >>messageitem%3c%3c %0a%3c Researchers in the Computer Science Department of IIT Kharagpur created an algorithm that, when given the written form of a Hindi word, predicts where the schwas will be deleted with 96.12 percent accuracy (tested on over 11000 words). The accuracy jumps to 99.89 percent when a morphological analyzer preprocesses the word and gives the algorithm information about the morphemes. The researchers create functions intended to be optimized (for example, the ease of articulation of a particular syllable) under certain constraints (for example, how much speakers can delete schwas before the meaning of the word becomes unclear). The algorithm tries to optimize these quantities, and has a runtime that is linear in the length of the word. The researchers also tested the algorithm on Bengali, in which case the accuracy was about 85 percent on 1000 randomly selected words. The researchers stress that their algorithm doesn't just outperform previous attempts; it also lays out a "constrained optimization based framework" to model phonological processes. %0a%3c %0a%3c Source: Choudhury, Monojit, Anupam Basu, and Sudeshna Sarkar. "A Diachronic Approach for Schwa Deletion in Indo-Aryan Languages" (2004)%0a%3c    %0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c #foxend 210330-222205-194770#%0a---%0a> %0a
